---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

export const meta = {
  title: "EtG Calculator: Alcohol Detection Time Estimator",
  description: "Estimate how long ethyl glucuronide (EtG) remains detectable in your system. Calculate alcohol clearance times before your next test.",
  category: "tool",
  published: "2026-03-15",
};

const schema = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How long does EtG stay in your system?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "EtG can stay in your system for up to 80 hours after heavy alcohol consumption, but it may clear much faster (24-48 hours) for light or moderate drinking."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the half-life of EtG?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The half-life of EtG is typically between 2 to 3 hours, meaning the concentration of EtG in your urine drops by half every 2 to 3 hours once your blood alcohol level hits zero."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can drinking water flush out EtG?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Drinking water can dilute your urine and temporarily lower the concentration of EtG, potentially dropping it below testing cutoffs, but it does not speed up the actual metabolism or 'flushing' of the biomarker from your body."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What does a 500 ng/mL cutoff mean?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "A 500 ng/mL cutoff is a standard threshold used in EtG testing. If the concentration of EtG in your urine is above 500 nanograms per milliliter, the test is considered positive for alcohol consumption."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can hand sanitizer cause a positive EtG test?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Incidental exposure to alcohol from products like hand sanitizers, mouthwash, or certain foods can occasionally cause low levels of EtG (usually under 500 ng/mL), which is why many testing facilities use higher cutoffs to differentiate between actual drinking and incidental exposure."
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": meta.title,
    "description": meta.description,
    "author": {
      "@type": "Organization",
      "name": "SiliconBased"
    }
  }
];
---
<SiteLayout site="siliconbased" title={meta.title} description={meta.description} canonical="https://siliconbased.dev/etg-calculator" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>{meta.title}</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Estimate EtG clearance time based on drinks consumed.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="calculator-container">
      <div class="input-group">
        <label for="drinks">Number of Standard Drinks Consumed</label>
        <input type="number" id="drinks" min="1" step="0.5" placeholder="e.g. 4">
        <div class="error-message" id="error-drinks">Please enter a valid number of drinks (minimum 1).</div>
      </div>
      <div class="input-group">
        <label for="hours-passed">Hours Since Last Drink</label>
        <input type="number" id="hours-passed" min="0" step="1" placeholder="e.g. 24">
        <div class="error-message" id="error-hours">Please enter a valid number of hours.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="input-group">
        <label for="cutoff">Test Cutoff Level (ng/mL)</label>
        <select id="cutoff">
          <option value="100">100 ng/mL (Very Strict)</option>
          <option value="500" selected>500 ng/mL (Standard)</option>
          <option value="1000">1000 ng/mL (Lenient)</option>
        </select>
      </div>

      <div class="result-card" id="result-container">
        <p>Estimated EtG Level</p>
        <div class="result-value" id="result-output">-- ng/mL</div>
        <p id="clearance-message" style="margin-top: 1rem; font-weight: 600;"></p>
        <p id="total-time" style="margin-top: 0.5rem; color: var(--text-secondary);"></p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="explainer">
      <h2>Understanding the EtG Calculator and Alcohol Detection</h2>
      <p>Whether required for a job, legal reasons, or personal accountability programs, alcohol testing has evolved significantly over the past decade. While traditional Breathalyzers or blood tests can only detect the presence of ethanol while you are actively intoxicated or shortly thereafter, modern testing often looks for specific biological markers left behind after your body metabolizes alcohol. The most common and reliable of these markers is Ethyl Glucuronide, commonly referred to as EtG. Our EtG Calculator is designed to help you estimate the concentration of this biomarker in your system and determine the approximate window of time required to pass a screening.</p>

      <h3>What is Ethyl Glucuronide (EtG)?</h3>
      <p>Ethyl Glucuronide (EtG) is a direct metabolite of ethanol, which is the intoxicating ingredient found in beer, wine, and liquor. When you consume alcohol, your body—specifically your liver—immediately begins the process of breaking it down to eliminate it from your system. A vast majority of ethanol is oxidized into acetaldehyde, but a tiny fraction (less than 0.1%) binds with glucuronic acid to form Ethyl Glucuronide. Because EtG is water-soluble, it is eventually filtered out by your kidneys and excreted in your urine.</p>
      <p>The crucial characteristic of EtG is that it lingers in the body much longer than ethanol itself. While pure alcohol might be completely cleared from your blood and breath within hours (at an average rate of about 0.015 BAC per hour), EtG can remain detectable in urine for several days. This makes EtG tests—often colloquially called "80-hour tests"—the preferred method for verifying continuous abstinence from alcohol.</p>

      <h3>How the Calculator Estimates Your Levels</h3>
      <p>Our calculator uses established pharmacokinetic models to provide an estimated clearance timeline. Estimating your current EtG level involves several variables, primarily the amount of alcohol consumed, the time elapsed since consumption, and the natural half-life of the metabolite.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Peak EtG Concentration:</strong> After you finish drinking, your blood alcohol concentration (BAC) will begin to fall, but your EtG levels will actually continue to rise as your liver processes the alcohol. EtG typically reaches its peak concentration in your urine around the exact moment your blood alcohol level drops to zero. The peak amount of EtG is directly correlated to the total volume of alcohol consumed. Generally, one standard drink translates to a peak urine EtG concentration of roughly 5,000 to 10,000 ng/mL, though this varies based on hydration, body mass, and individual metabolism.</li>
        <li><strong>The Half-Life of EtG:</strong> Once EtG has peaked, it begins to clear from your system exponentially. The widely accepted half-life of EtG in healthy adults is between 2 to 3 hours. This means that every 2.5 hours, the concentration of EtG in your urine drops by half. For instance, if your peak level was 10,000 ng/mL, after 2.5 hours it would drop to 5,000 ng/mL, then to 2,500 ng/mL after 5 hours, and so forth.</li>
        <li><strong>Calculating the Timeline:</strong> To use the calculator, you enter the number of standard drinks you consumed and the hours that have passed since your last drink. The calculator assumes a standard absorption and metabolism period to determine when your BAC hits zero and your EtG peaks. It then applies the half-life decay formula to estimate your current EtG level.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Understanding Test Cutoffs</h3>
      <p>An essential aspect of EtG testing is the "cutoff level"—the specific concentration threshold at which a test is triggered as positive. If your EtG level is below the cutoff, the test is reported as negative, even if trace amounts of the biomarker are technically present.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>100 ng/mL (Very Strict):</strong> This is an incredibly sensitive cutoff, often used in zero-tolerance monitoring programs. A cutoff this low can catch light drinking up to 48 hours later, but it is also highly susceptible to false positives from incidental alcohol exposure, such as using mouthwash containing alcohol, applying large amounts of hand sanitizer, or consuming foods prepared with cooking wine or vanilla extract.</li>
        <li><strong>500 ng/mL (Standard):</strong> This is the most common cutoff used by courts, probation departments, and workplace testing. It provides a reliable balance, catching moderate to heavy drinking episodes up to 48-72 hours later, while effectively filtering out the "background noise" of incidental, non-beverage alcohol exposure.</li>
        <li><strong>1,000 ng/mL (Lenient):</strong> Used to confirm recent, heavy drinking. While a test with this cutoff might miss a couple of beers consumed a day prior, it is virtually immune to false positives from incidental exposure.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Limitations and Real-World Variables</h3>
      <p>While the mathematical models behind our calculator provide a solid estimate, it is vital to remember that human biology is not perfectly precise. Dozens of variables can alter how quickly your body clears EtG.</p>
      <p>Hydration plays a massive role. Because EtG is excreted in urine, drinking large volumes of water will dilute the concentration of the biomarker in your sample. This is why highly diluted urine samples are often flagged by testing labs as "invalid" or "tampered." Conversely, if you are severely dehydrated, the EtG in your urine becomes highly concentrated, potentially causing a positive result much later than the calculator might suggest.</p>
      <p>Other factors include your liver health, kidney function, age, and metabolism speed. Additionally, a "standard drink" (defined in the US as 14 grams of pure alcohol, equivalent to a 12oz 5% beer, a 5oz 12% wine, or a 1.5oz shot of 40% liquor) is often smaller than the heavy pours typical in bars or at home. If you underestimate the amount you drank, the calculator will underestimate your clearance time.</p>

      <p><em>Disclaimer: This calculator is designed for informational and educational purposes only. It cannot guarantee test results. Always consult testing professionals or medical experts regarding alcohol metabolism and screening policies.</em></p>

      <div class="related-tools">
        <h3>Related Tools</h3>
        <p>Planning outdoor winter activities safely? Check out our <a href="/ice-tracker">Ice Tracker</a> to estimate safe ice thickness based on temperatures.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>How long does EtG stay in your system?</summary>
        <p>While commonly called the "80-hour test," EtG rarely stays detectable for 80 hours unless you consume a very large amount of alcohol. For light drinking (1-2 drinks), EtG usually clears below standard cutoffs within 24 to 36 hours. Heavy drinking can result in positive tests for 48 to 72 hours, depending on the test's sensitivity.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is the half-life of EtG?</summary>
        <p>The biological half-life of EtG is approximately 2.5 hours (ranging between 2 to 3 hours). This means that once the biomarker peaks in your system, its concentration in your urine drops by roughly 50% every two and a half hours.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Can drinking water flush out EtG?</summary>
        <p>Drinking excessive amounts of water does not force your liver or kidneys to metabolize EtG faster. However, it does artificially dilute your urine, which can temporarily lower the concentration of EtG per milliliter below the testing cutoff. Most modern labs test for creatinine levels and specific gravity to detect diluted samples, which can result in a failed or invalid test.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What does a 500 ng/mL cutoff mean?</summary>
        <p>A 500 ng/mL cutoff is the most common testing threshold. "ng/mL" stands for nanograms per milliliter. If the concentration of EtG in your urine sample is above 500, the test is positive. This level is high enough to ignore trace alcohol exposure from things like hand sanitizer, but low enough to catch moderate to heavy drinking.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Can hand sanitizer cause a positive EtG test?</summary>
        <p>Yes, but usually only at very sensitive testing levels (like a 100 ng/mL cutoff). Heavy, repeated use of alcohol-based hand sanitizer or alcohol-containing mouthwash can result in trace amounts of EtG forming in the body. Standard 500 ng/mL cutoffs are specifically designed to ignore these false positives.</p>
      </details>
    </section>
  </div>

  <script is:inline>
    document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
      const drinksInput = document.getElementById('drinks');
      const hoursInput = document.getElementById('hours-passed');
      const cutoffSelect = document.getElementById('cutoff');

      const errorDrinks = document.getElementById('error-drinks');
      const errorHours = document.getElementById('error-hours');

      const resultContainer = document.getElementById('result-container');
      const resultOutput = document.getElementById('result-output');
      const clearanceMessage = document.getElementById('clearance-message');
      const totalTimeMessage = document.getElementById('total-time');

      function calculateEtG() {
        const drinksRaw = drinksInput.value;
        const hoursRaw = hoursInput.value;

        // Reset errors
        errorDrinks.style.display = 'none';
        errorHours.style.display = 'none';

        if (drinksRaw === '' || hoursRaw === '') {
          resultContainer.style.display = 'none';
          return;
        }

        const drinks = parseFloat(drinksRaw);
        const hoursPassed = parseFloat(hoursRaw);
        const cutoff = parseInt(cutoffSelect.value, 10);

        let hasError = false;

        if (isNaN(drinks) || drinks < 1) {
          errorDrinks.style.display = 'block';
          hasError = true;
        }

        if (isNaN(hoursPassed) || hoursPassed < 0) {
          errorHours.style.display = 'block';
          hasError = true;
        }

        if (hasError) {
          resultContainer.style.display = 'none';
          return;
        }

        // Calculation logic for EtG
        // Assume BAC clears at roughly 1 drink per hour. EtG peaks when BAC hits 0.
        // Peak EtG roughly ~ 10,000 ng/mL per drink.
        // Half life is approx 2.5 hours.

        const hoursToPeak = drinks; // Roughly 1 hour per drink to hit 0 BAC and peak EtG
        const peakEtG = drinks * 10000;

        let currentEtG = 0;

        if (hoursPassed <= hoursToPeak) {
          // Linear rise to peak
          currentEtG = (hoursPassed / hoursToPeak) * peakEtG;
        } else {
          // Exponential decay after peak
          const decayHours = hoursPassed - hoursToPeak;
          const halfLives = decayHours / 2.5;
          currentEtG = peakEtG * Math.pow(0.5, halfLives);
        }

        // Calculate total time to clear below cutoff
        // cutoff = peak * (0.5 ^ (t / 2.5))
        // log(cutoff / peak) = (t / 2.5) * log(0.5)
        // t = 2.5 * (log(cutoff / peak) / log(0.5))
        // total time = hoursToPeak + t
        let totalTimeToClear = hoursToPeak;
        if (peakEtG > cutoff) {
          const decayTimeToClear = 2.5 * (Math.log(cutoff / peakEtG) / Math.log(0.5));
          totalTimeToClear += decayTimeToClear;
        }

        // Display results
        resultOutput.textContent = Math.round(currentEtG).toLocaleString() + ' ng/mL';
        resultContainer.style.display = 'block';

        if (currentEtG < cutoff) {
          clearanceMessage.textContent = "Estimated level is BELOW the cutoff.";
          clearanceMessage.style.color = "#22c55e"; // Green
        } else {
          clearanceMessage.textContent = "Estimated level is ABOVE the cutoff.";
          clearanceMessage.style.color = "#ef4444"; // Red
        }

        totalTimeMessage.textContent = `Estimated total time to fall below ${cutoff} ng/mL: ${totalTimeToClear.toFixed(1)} hours from your first drink.`;
      }

      drinksInput.addEventListener('input', calculateEtG);
      hoursInput.addEventListener('input', calculateEtG);
      cutoffSelect.addEventListener('change', calculateEtG);
    });
  </script>

  <style is:inline>
    .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
    .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.2rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .subtitle { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.1rem; }
    .calculator-container { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 2rem; margin: 2rem 0; }
    input, select { background: var(--bg-color); color: var(--text-primary); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); padding: 0.75rem 1rem; border-radius: 8px; width: 100%; font-size: 1rem; }
    input:focus, select:focus { outline: none; border-color: var(--accent-color); box-shadow: 0 0 0 3px color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 20%, transparent); }
    button { background: var(--accent-color); color: white; border: none; padding: 0.75rem 2rem; border-radius: 8px; font-weight: 600; cursor: pointer; font-size: 1rem; }
    button:hover { opacity: 0.9; }
    .result-card { background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 10%, transparent); border: 1px solid var(--accent-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; margin: 1.5rem 0; text-align: center; display: none; }
    .result-value { font-size: 2.5rem; font-weight: 800; color: var(--accent-color); }
    .faq-section details { margin: 1rem 0; padding: 1rem; background: var(--card-bg); border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    .faq-section summary { font-weight: 600; cursor: pointer; }
    .input-group { margin-bottom: 1.5rem; text-align: left; }
    .input-group label { display: block; font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .error-message { color: #ef4444; font-size: 0.875rem; margin-top: 0.5rem; display: none; }
    .explainer p { margin-bottom: 1rem; line-height: 1.6; }
    .explainer h2, .explainer h3 { margin: 2rem 0 1rem; }
    .explainer ul { margin-bottom: 1rem; padding-left: 1.5rem; }
    .explainer li { margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .related-tools { margin-bottom: 2rem; padding: 1.5rem; background: var(--card-bg); border-radius: 12px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    .related-tools a { color: var(--accent-color); font-weight: 600; text-decoration: none; }
    .related-tools a:hover { text-decoration: underline; }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>
